The promise — and what they do not do.

Type hints since python three point five let you annotate parameters and return values with the types they expect. The shape — def greet, name colon string, times colon integer equals one, arrow string, body returns the formatted string.

The promise. Tools — my-py, py-right, your i-d-e — check your code statically and flag mismatches before you run. Humans read the signature and know what to pass. Refactors become safer — rename a class and the type checker shows every site that needs updating.

What hints do not do — they do not enforce anything at runtime. Python ignores them when executing your code. Calling greet of forty-two and no runs without error until the string operations in the body fail. If you want runtime validation, reach for pydantic or write is-instance checks yourself.

The mental model. Type hints are like comments that the type checker reads. The interpreter does not.

In code, picture greet returning the formatted string. Greet of ganesh works. Greet of alice and three works. Runtime does not enforce the hints — greet of forty-two and no runs and fails inside the body with a type error. A type checker like my-py would have flagged the call before you ran.
